company.name: TeleCheck Services, Inc.
company.business_description: TeleCheck provides check authorization services and recommendations to merchants throughout the United States regarding whether to accept consumers' checks. TeleCheck has processed 560 million transactions for over 400,000 subscribers at more than 375,000 locations, taking into account consumer identification, unpaid debts in the form of previous returned checks, and various risk factors.

case_info.legal_authority: Section 5(a) of the Federal Trade Commission Act, 15 U.S.C. § 45(a); Section 621(a) of the Fair Credit Reporting Act, 15 U.S.C. § 1681s(a)

complaint.factual_background: TeleCheck Services, Inc., a consumer reporting agency that provides check authorization recommendations to merchants, and its affiliate TRS Recovery Services, Inc., violated the Fair Credit Reporting Act and FTC Act. TeleCheck failed to properly reinvestigate disputed consumer information, failed to follow reasonable procedures to ensure accuracy of consumer reports, and TRS failed to establish proper written policies regarding the accuracy and integrity of information it furnished to TeleCheck. These failures exposed consumers to inaccurate reporting that could result in denial of their ability to pay by check at thousands of merchant locations.

representations_made.description: TeleCheck represented it would conduct reasonable reinvestigations to determine whether disputed information is accurate as required by FCRA
representations_made.quoted_text: 18. Upon receiving a dispute from the consumer, the FCRA requires that TeleCheck conduct a reasonable reinvestigation to determine whether the disputed information is accurate. See section 611(a)(1)(A) of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681i(a)(1)(A).

representations_made.description: TeleCheck represented it would follow reasonable procedures to assure maximum possible accuracy of consumer report information
representations_made.quoted_text: 22. Section 607(b) of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681e(b), requires CRAs to follow reasonable procedures to “assure the maximum possible accuracy of the information concerning the individual about whom the report relates.”

representations_made.description: TRS represented it would establish and implement reasonable written policies and procedures regarding accuracy and integrity of consumer information furnished to CRAs
representations_made.quoted_text: 25. The Furnisher Rule, 16 C.F.R. § 660, recodified at 12 C.F.R. § 1022, subpart E, states that furnishers must establish and implement reasonable written policies and procedures regarding the accuracy and integrity of the information relating to consumers that they furnish to 9

counts.title: Reinvestigations of Disputed Information
counts.representation: TeleCheck was required to follow the steps required by section 611 of the FCRA, including completing reasonable reinvestigations within 30-45 days, providing prompt notice of disputes to furnishers, deleting inaccurate information, and providing proper notice to consumers
counts.fact: TeleCheck failed to complete reinvestigations within required timeframes, failed to provide prompt notice of disputes to furnishers, failed to delete inaccurate or unverifiable information, failed to maintain procedures to prevent reappearance of deleted information, and failed to provide proper notice to consumers of investigation results
counts.conclusion: TeleCheck has violated section 611 of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681i, and these acts constitute unfair or deceptive acts or practices in violation of section 5(a) of the FTC Act.

counts.title: Accuracy of Consumer Report Information
counts.representation: TeleCheck was required to use reasonable procedures to assure maximum possible accuracy of consumer report information as required by section 607(b) of the FCRA
counts.fact: TeleCheck failed to follow reasonable procedures to assure maximum possible accuracy by failing to promptly delete or modify inaccurate or unverifiable information from consumer files after conducting reinvestigations, increasing the risk of reporting inaccurate information
counts.conclusion: TeleCheck has violated section 607(b) of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681e(b), and these acts constitute unfair or deceptive acts or practices in violation of section 5(a) of the FTC Act.

counts.title: Requirements of Furnishers: Written Policies
counts.representation: TRS was required to consider the guidelines in appendix E of the Furnisher Rule and establish reasonable written policies and procedures regarding the accuracy and integrity of information it furnishes to CRAs
counts.fact: TRS failed to consider the guidelines in appendix E of the Furnisher Rule in its written policies and procedures regarding the accuracy and integrity of the information relating to consumers that it furnishes to TeleCheck
counts.conclusion: TRS has violated 16 C.F.R. § 660.3(a), recodified at 12 C.F.R. § 1022.42(a), and these acts constitute unfair or deceptive acts or practices in violation of section 5(a) of the FTC Act.

definitions.Defendants: TeleCheck Services, Inc. ("TeleCheck") and TRS Recovery Services, Inc. ("TRS"), their subsidiaries and operating companies, and their successors and assigns.
definitions.Person: any individual, partnership, corporation, trust, estate, cooperative, association, government or governmental subdivision or agency, or other entity.
definitions.Consumer Report: any written, oral, or other communication of any information by a CRA bearing on a consumer's credit worthiness, credit standing, credit capacity, character, general reputation, personal characteristics, or mode of living which is used or expected to be used or collected in whole or in part for the purpose of serving as a factor in establishing the consumer's eligibility for (1) credit or insurance to be used primarily for personal, family, or household purposes; (2) employment purposes; or (3) any other purpose authorized under section 604 of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681b. For exclusions, see section 603(d)(2) of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681a(d)(2), a copy of which is attached as Exhibit A.
definitions.Consumer Reporting Agency: any person which, for monetary fees, dues, or on a cooperative nonprofit basis, regularly engages in whole or in part in the practice of assembling or evaluating consumer credit information or other information on consumers for the purpose of furnishing consumer reports to third parties, and which uses any means or facility of interstate commerce for the purpose of preparing or furnishing consumer reports.

provisions.title: Civil Penalty
provisions.summary: Defendants must pay a civil penalty of $3,500,000 to the United States within seven days of entry of this Order.

requirements.description: Pay civil penalty of $3,500,000 to the Treasurer of the United States by electronic fund transfer
requirements.quoted_text: Defendants are ordered to pay Plaintiff, by making payment to the Treasurer of the United States, three million five hundred thousand dollars ($3,500,000) within seven (7) days of entry of this Order by electronic fund transfer in accordance with instructions previously provided by a representative of Plaintiff.

provisions.title: Additional Monetary Provisions
provisions.summary: If Defendants default on payment obligations, the judgment amount becomes immediately due with interest. Defendants relinquish all rights to assets transferred under this Order.

requirements.description: If in default, judgment amount with interest becomes immediately due
requirements.quoted_text: A. If Defendants are in default on any obligations under this Section, then the judgment amount, together with interest computed pursuant to 28 U.S.C. § 1961 from the date of default to the date of payment, minus any payments previously made pursuant to this Section, becomes immediately due.

requirements.description: Relinquish dominion and all legal and equitable right, title, and interest in all assets transferred pursuant to this Order
requirements.quoted_text: B. Defendants relinquish dominion and all legal and equitable right, title, and interest in all assets transferred pursuant to this Order and may not seek the return of any assets.

provisions.title: Prohibited Business Activities as to TeleCheck
provisions.summary: TeleCheck is permanently restrained from violating FCRA sections 611 and 607(b) in connection with its activities as a consumer reporting agency.

requirements.description: Must not require the consumer to contact a third party directly to resolve a dispute over completeness or accuracy of information in the consumer's file
requirements.quoted_text: 1. Requiring the consumer to contact a third party directly to resolve a dispute over the completeness or accuracy of any item of information contained in the consumer's file;

requirements.description: Must not impose limitations or conditions before conducting a reinvestigation unless such limitations or conditions are expressly allowed by the FCRA
requirements.quoted_text: 2. Imposing limitations or conditions before conducting a reinvestigation unless such limitations or conditions are expressly allowed by the FCRA;

requirements.description: Must not fail to complete reinvestigations of disputes within 30 days or 45 days if information is received during the 30-day period, and must adequately track the handling and resolution of consumer disputes to ensure their timely resolution
requirements.quoted_text: 3. Failing to complete reinvestigations of disputes within 30 days or, if TeleCheck receives information from the consumer during that 30-day period that is relevant to the reinvestigation, within 45 days, and failing to adequately track the handling and resolution of consumer disputes to ensure their timely resolution;

requirements.description: Must not fail to provide notification of the dispute to any person who provided any item of information in dispute within 5 business days of receiving notice of dispute, including all relevant information regarding the dispute
requirements.quoted_text: 4. Failing to provide, before the expiration of the 5-business-day period beginning on the date on which TeleCheck receives notice of a dispute from any consumer, notification of the dispute to any person who provided any item of information in dispute, at the address and in the manner established with the person, which includes all relevant information regarding the dispute that TeleCheck has received from the consumer;

requirements.description: Must not fail to notify the consumer within 5 business days when it has terminated a reinvestigation because it reasonably determined that the consumer's dispute was frivolous or irrelevant
requirements.quoted_text: 5. Failing to notify the consumer, within 5 business days, by mail or other means authorized by the consumer for that purpose, when it has terminated a reinvestigation of information disputed by a consumer, because it reasonably determined that the consumer's dispute was frivolous or irrelevant;

requirements.description: After conducting a reinvestigation and finding that an item of information is inaccurate, incomplete, or cannot be verified, must not fail to promptly delete or modify the item and promptly notify the furnisher that the information has been modified or deleted
requirements.quoted_text: 6. After conducting a reinvestigation of any information disputed by a consumer and finding that an item of information is inaccurate, incomplete, or cannot be verified, failing to: i. promptly delete or modify an item of information from the consumer's file, as appropriate, based on the results of the reinvestigation; and ii. promptly notify the furnisher of that information that the information has been modified or deleted from the consumer's file;

requirements.description: Must not fail to maintain reasonable procedures designed to prevent the reappearance in a consumer's file of information that is deleted pursuant to a reinvestigation
requirements.quoted_text: 7. Failing to maintain reasonable procedures designed to prevent the reappearance in a consumer's file, and in consumer reports on the consumer, of information that is deleted pursuant to a reinvestigation;

requirements.description: Must not fail to provide written notice to a consumer of the results of a reinvestigation not later than five business days after the completion of the reinvestigation
requirements.quoted_text: 8. Failing to provide written notice to a consumer of the results of a reinvestigation not later than five (5) business days after the completion of the reinvestigation;

requirements.description: Must not fail to comply with section 607(b) of the FCRA by failing to promptly delete or modify an item of information after conducting a reinvestigation and finding that it was inaccurate or unverifiable
requirements.quoted_text: B. Failing to comply with section 607(b) ofthe FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681e(b), a copy of which is attached as Exhibit C, including by failing to promptly delete or modify an item of information from the consumer's file after conducting a reinvestigation and finding that an item of information was inaccurate or unverifiable.

provisions.title: Prohibited Business Activities as to TRS
provisions.summary: TRS is permanently restrained from failing to comply with the Furnisher Rule, including by failing to consider the guidelines in 12 C.F.R. § 1022, subpart E, in TRS's written policies and procedures.

requirements.description: Must not fail to comply with 12 C.F.R. § 1022.42, including by failing to consider the guidelines in 12 C.F.R. § 1022, subpart E, in TRS's written policies and procedures
requirements.quoted_text: A. Failing to comply with 12 C.P.R.§ 1022.42, a copy of which is attached as Exhibit D, including by failing to consider the guidelines in 12 C.P.R.§ 1022, subpart E, in TRS' s written policies and procedures.

provisions.title: Order Acknowledgments
provisions.summary: Defendants must submit acknowledgments of receipt of this Order and deliver copies to personnel and business entities for five years.

requirements.description: Each Defendant must submit to the Commission an acknowledgment of receipt of this Order sworn under penalty of perjury
requirements.quoted_text: A. Each Defendant, within seven (7) days of entry of this Order, must submit to the Commission an acknowledgment of receipt of this Order sworn under penalty of perjury.

requirements.description: For five years after entry of this Order, each Defendant must deliver a copy of this Order to all principals, officers, directors, LLC managers and members, employees and agents who participate in conduct related to the subject matter, and any business entity resulting from change in structure
requirements.quoted_text: B. For five (5) years after entry of this Order, each Defendant for any business that such Defendant, individually or collectively with any other Defendant, is the majority owner or controls directly or indirectly, must deliver a copy of this Order to: (1) all principals, officers, directors, and LLC managers and members; (2) all employees, agents, and representatives who participate in conduct related to the subject matter of the Order; and (3) any business entity resulting from any change in structure as set forth in the Section titled Compliance Reporting. Delivery must occur within seven (7) days of entry of this Order for current personnel. For all others, delivery must occur before they assume their responsibilities.

requirements.description: From each individual or entity to which a Defendant delivered a copy of this Order, that Defendant must obtain a signed and dated acknowledgment of receipt of this Order
requirements.quoted_text: C. From each individual or entity to which a Defendant delivered a copy of this Order, that Defendant must obtain, within thirty (30) days, a signed and dated acknowledgment of receipt of this Order.

provisions.title: Compliance Reporting
provisions.summary: Defendants must submit compliance reports and notices to the Commission at specified intervals and upon certain triggering events.

requirements.description: Each Defendant must submit a compliance report, sworn under penalty of perjury, identifying contact information, all businesses, activities of each business, compliance with each Section of this Order, and copies of Order Acknowledgments
requirements.quoted_text: A. One hundred eighty (180) days after entry of this Order, each Defendant must submit a compliance report, sworn under penalty of perjury. Each Defendant must: (I) identify the primary physical, postal, and email address and telephone number, as designated points of contact, which representatives of the Commission or Plaintiff may use to communicate with Defendant; (2) identify all of that Defendant's businesses by all of their names, primary telephone numbers, and physical, postal, email, and Internet addresses; (3) describe the activities of each business, including the products and services offered, the means of consumer reporting and debt collection, and, the involvement of any other Defendant; (4 ) describe in detail whether and how that Defendant is in compliance with each Section of this Order; and (5) provide a copy of each Order Acknowledgment obtained pursuant to this Order, unless previously submitted to the Commission.

requirements.description: For ten years after entry of this Order, each Defendant must submit a compliance notice, sworn under penalty of perjury, within fourteen days of any change in designated point of contact or structure of Defendant or any entity that Defendant has any ownership interest in or controls
requirements.quoted_text: B. For ten (1 0) years after entry of this Order, each Defendant must submit a compliance notice, sworn under penalty of perjury, within fourteen (14) days of any change in the following: (1) any designated point of contact; or (2) the structure of Defendant or any entity that Defendant has any ownership interest in or directly or indirectly controls that may affect compliance obligations arising under this Order, including: creation, merger, sale, or dissolution of the entity or any subsidiary, parent, or affiliate that engages in any acts or practices of subject to this Order.

requirements.description: Each Defendant must submit to the Commission notice of the filing of any bankruptcy petition, insolvency proceeding, or similar proceeding within fourteen days of its filing
requirements.quoted_text: C. Each Defendant must submit to the Commission notice of the filing of any bankruptcy petition, insolvency proceeding, or any similar proceeding by or against such Defendant within fourteen ( 14) days of its filing.

provisions.title: Recordkeeping Provisions
provisions.summary: Defendants must create and retain records for specified periods, including accounting records, personnel records, consumer complaints, training materials, dispute files, and compliance records.

requirements.description: Must create certain records for ten years after entry of the Order, and retain each such record for five years, including accounting records, personnel records, consumer complaints, training materials and written policies, consumer dispute files, and all records necessary to demonstrate full compliance with this Order
requirements.quoted_text: IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that Defendants must create certain records for ten (10) years after entry of the Order, and retain each such record for five (5) years. Specifically, Defendants, in connection with providing consumer reports, must create and retain the following records: A. Accounting records showing the revenues from all goods or services sold, all costs incurred in generating those revenues, and the resulting net profit or loss; B. Personnel records showing, for each person providing services, whether as an employee or otherwise, that person's: name, addresses, and telephone numbers; job title or position; dates of service; and, (if applicable) the reason for termination; C. Consumer complaints, whether received directly or indirectly, such as through a third party, and any response; D. Copies of all training materials and written policies and procedures that relate to Defendants' activities in consumer reporting or debt-collection or Defendants' compliance with the provisions of this Order; 9 Case 1:14-cv-00062-CKK Document 3 Filed 01/17/14 Page 10 of 30 E. Consumer dispute files that include correspondence between consumers and Defendants, and correspondence between Defendants and furnishers of disputed information, sufficient to demonstrate compliance with section 611 of the FCRA, 15 U.S.C. § 1681, a copy of which is attached as Exhibit B; and F. All records and documents necessary to demonstrate full compliance with each provision of this Order, including all submissions to the Commission.

provisions.title: Compliance Monitoring
provisions.summary: The Commission and Plaintiff are authorized to monitor Defendants' compliance through various means including requesting documents, depositions, interviews, and posing as consumers.

requirements.description: Within fourteen days of receipt of a written request from a representative of Commission or Plaintiff, each Defendant must submit additional compliance reports or other requested information, appear for depositions, and produce documents for inspection and copying
requirements.quoted_text: A. Within fourteen ( 14) days of receipt of a written request from a representative of Commission or Plaintiff, each Defendant must: submit additional compliance reports or other requested information, which must be sworn under penalty of perjury; appear for depositions; and produce documents for inspection and copying. The Commission and Plaintiff are also authorized to obtain discovery, without further leave of court, using any of the procedures prescribed by Federal Rules of Civil Procedure 29, 30 (including telephonic depositions), 31, 33, 34, 36, 45, and 69, provided that Defendant, after attempting to resolve a dispute without court action and for good cause shown, may file a motion with this Court seeking an order including one or more of the protections set forth in Rule 26( c).

requirements.description: Defendants must permit representatives of the Commission and Plaintiff to interview any employee or other person affiliated with any Defendant who has agreed to such an interview
requirements.quoted_text: communicate directly with each Defendant. Defendants must permit representatives of the Commission and Plaintiff to interview any employee or other person affiliated with any Defendant who has agreed to such an interview. The person interviewed may have counsel present.

requirements.description: The Commission and Plaintiff may use all other lawful means, including posing as consumers, suppliers, or other individuals or entities, to Defendants or any individual or entity affiliated with Defendants, without the necessity of identification or prior notice
requirements.quoted_text: C. The Commission and Plaintiff may use all other lawful means, including posing, through its representatives, as consumers, suppliers, or other individuals or entities, to Defendants or any individual or entity affiliated with Defendants, without the necessity of identification or prior notice. Nothing in this Order limits the Commission's lawful use of compulsory process, pursuant to sections 9 and 20 ofthe FTC Act, 15 U.S.C. §§ 49, 57b-1.

provisions.title: Retention of Jurisdiction
provisions.summary: The Court retains jurisdiction of this matter for purposes of construction, modification, and enforcement of this Order.

requirements.description: This Court retains jurisdiction of this matter for purposes of construction, modification, and enforcement of this Order
requirements.quoted_text: IT IS FURTHER ORDERED that this Court retains jurisdiction ofthis matter for purposes of construction, modification, and enforcement of this Order.

duration.termination_text: This Court retains jurisdiction of this matter for purposes of construction, modification, and enforcement of this Order.
